{"title": "What you need to know about Trump\u2019s travel ban", "url": "http://nypost.com/2017/06/27/what-you-need-to-know-about-trumps-travel-ban/", "text": "The Supreme Court on Monday allowed the Trump administration to...\n\nHighlights of Monday\u2019s US Supreme Court decision allowing a limited version of the Trump administration\u2019s travel ban to go into effect:\n\n90-day travel ban\n\nCountries it applies to:\n\nIran, Libya, Somalia, Sudan, Syria and Yemen\n\nWho can still get a visa?\n\n\u201cForeign nationals who have a credible claim of a bona fide relationship with a person or entity in the United States,\u201d the court said.\n\n\u201cAs for entities, the relationship must be formal, documented, and formed in the ordinary course, rather than for the purpose of evading [the order],\u201d it added.\n\nThat includes:\n\nPeople who have \u201ca close familial relationship\u201d with someone in the US. \u201cA foreign national who wishes to enter the United States to live with or visit a family member . . . clearly has such a relationship,\u201d the court ruled.\n\nA student admitted to an American university.\n\nA worker who takes a job with an American company.\n\nA lecturer invited to speak before an American audience.\n\nWho can\u2019t get a visa?\n\nVisa applicants without a \u201cbona fide relationship with a person or entity\u201d in the US.\n\n120-day refugee ban\n\nWhich refugees can\u2019t enter the US?\n\nThose who lack a \u201cbona fide relationship\u201d with a person or entity in the US. \u201cWhen it comes to refugees who lack any such connection to the United States, for the reasons we have set out, the balance tips in favor of the Government\u2019s compelling need to provide for the Nation\u2019s security,\u201d the court said.", "source": "New York Post", "publish_date": "2017-06-27", "type": "article"}